<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="69" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="68">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="68">
A few years after the description of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. bertiae" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" rank="species" species="bertiae">S. bertiae</taxonomicName>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Jolivet, P" journalOrPublisher="Nouvelle Revue d'Entomologie" pageId="7" pageNumber="72" pagination="141 - 154" title="New and known leaf beetles collected in Mont Panie in 2010 (Coleoptera, Chrysomelidae, Eumolpinae)." volume="29" year="2013">Jolivet et al. (2013)</bibRefCitation>
described another species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Baly, 1867" authorityName="Baly" authorityYear="1867" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Stethotes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Stethotes" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Stethotes</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. jourdani" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" rank="species" species="jourdani">S. jourdani</taxonomicName>
, very similar to the former but with subtler punctation and from localities further north in the island, in the Massif du 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Panié">Panie</normalizedToken>
, including La Guen, Dawenia, and Wewec (
<bibRefCitation author="Jolivet, P" journalOrPublisher="Nouvelle Revue d'Entomologie" pageId="7" pageNumber="72" pagination="141 - 154" title="New and known leaf beetles collected in Mont Panie in 2010 (Coleoptera, Chrysomelidae, Eumolpinae)." volume="29" year="2013">Jolivet et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
). As before, the species does not have any of the characters of the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Baly, 1867" authorityName="Baly" authorityYear="1867" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Stethotes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Stethotes" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Stethotes</taxonomicName>
, but these of 
<taxonomicName authority="Samuelson, 2015" authorityName="Samuelson" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Acronymolpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acronymolpus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Acronymolpus</taxonomicName>
instead. Interestingly, it fits the description of the second blackish species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Samuelson, 2015" authorityName="Samuelson" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Acronymolpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acronymolpus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Acronymolpus</taxonomicName>
described by A. Samuelson a couple of years later, 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. gressitti" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" rank="species" species="gressitti">A. gressitti</taxonomicName>
, also collected from Mt. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Panié">Panie</normalizedToken>
. It is worth noting that both descriptions depart in a significant character: the size of the holotypes. The type of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. jourdani" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" rank="species" species="jourdani">S. jourdani</taxonomicName>
is reported as 4.0 mm long (
<bibRefCitation author="Jolivet, P" journalOrPublisher="Nouvelle Revue d'Entomologie" pageId="7" pageNumber="72" pagination="141 - 154" title="New and known leaf beetles collected in Mont Panie in 2010 (Coleoptera, Chrysomelidae, Eumolpinae)." volume="29" year="2013">Jolivet et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
), while that of 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. gressitti" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" rank="species" species="gressitti">A. gressitti</taxonomicName>
is 2.6 mm (
<bibRefCitation author="Samuelson, GA" editor="Jolivet, P" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="7" pageNumber="72" pagination="93 - 102" title="Acronymolpus, a new genus of Eumolpinae, endemic to New Caledonia (Coleoptera, Chrysomelidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.547.9698" volume="547" volumeTitle="Research on Chrysomelidae 5." year="2015">Samuelson 2015</bibRefCitation>
). The measurement given by 
<bibRefCitation author="Jolivet, P" journalOrPublisher="Nouvelle Revue d'Entomologie" pageId="7" pageNumber="72" pagination="141 - 154" title="New and known leaf beetles collected in Mont Panie in 2010 (Coleoptera, Chrysomelidae, Eumolpinae)." volume="29" year="2013">Jolivet et al. (2013)</bibRefCitation>
is far bigger than the largest 
<taxonomicName authority="Samuelson, 2015" authorityName="Samuelson" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Acronymolpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acronymolpus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Acronymolpus</taxonomicName>
studied by 
<bibRefCitation author="Samuelson, GA" editor="Jolivet, P" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="7" pageNumber="72" pagination="93 - 102" title="Acronymolpus, a new genus of Eumolpinae, endemic to New Caledonia (Coleoptera, Chrysomelidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.547.9698" volume="547" volumeTitle="Research on Chrysomelidae 5." year="2015">Samuelson (2015)</bibRefCitation>
. However, it is important to note that, judging from the figures in the article, the measurements in 
<bibRefCitation author="Jolivet, P" journalOrPublisher="Nouvelle Revue d'Entomologie" pageId="7" pageNumber="72" pagination="141 - 154" title="New and known leaf beetles collected in Mont Panie in 2010 (Coleoptera, Chrysomelidae, Eumolpinae)." volume="29" year="2013">Jolivet et al. (2013)</bibRefCitation>
may not be reliable. 
<taxonomicName authority="Jolivet, Verma &amp; Mille, 2007" authorityName="Jolivet, Verma &amp; Mille" authorityYear="2007" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Samuelsonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Samuelsonia gomyi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gomyi">Samuelsonia gomyi</taxonomicName>
Jolivet et al., 2013 measures 2.5 mm and it shows slightly longer than the holotype of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. jourdani" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" rank="species" species="jourdani">S. jourdani</taxonomicName>
, figured alongside and possibly photographed with the same magnification as the former, since both show an identical scale bar of 2.0 mm (
<bibRefCitation author="Jolivet, P" journalOrPublisher="Nouvelle Revue d'Entomologie" pageId="7" pageNumber="72" pagination="141 - 154" title="New and known leaf beetles collected in Mont Panie in 2010 (Coleoptera, Chrysomelidae, Eumolpinae)." volume="29" year="2013">Jolivet et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
, figs 7 and 8). Apart from this detail, the two species, 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. jourdani" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" rank="species" species="jourdani">S. jourdani</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. gressitti" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" rank="species" species="gressitti">A. gressitti</taxonomicName>
, match in their characters, as recognized by the author of the latter (G. Allan Samuelson, pers. comm.), including the four basal antennomeres paler, vertex deeply sulcate, smooth hypomera, and pronotal and elytral punctation smaller than in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. bertiae" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" rank="species" species="bertiae">S. bertiae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="69" pageId="3" pageNumber="68">
Moreover, additional material, even if limited, made it possible to draw an analogy with the previous case whereby 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. joliveti" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" rank="species" species="joliveti">A. joliveti</taxonomicName>
could be recognized as the female of 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. gressitti" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" rank="species" species="gressitti">A. gressitti</taxonomicName>
. The spermatheca of this species was known due to the description of 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. joliveti" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" rank="species" species="joliveti">A. joliveti</taxonomicName>
, and the only information available on the male genitalia was a drawing of the penis in lateral view (
<bibRefCitation author="Jolivet, P" journalOrPublisher="Nouvelle Revue d'Entomologie" pageId="7" pageNumber="72" pagination="141 - 154" title="New and known leaf beetles collected in Mont Panie in 2010 (Coleoptera, Chrysomelidae, Eumolpinae)." volume="29" year="2013">Jolivet et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 1). The spermatheca of 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. jourdani" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" rank="species" species="jourdani">A. jourdani</taxonomicName>
, figured here from a specimen from 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Mandjélia">Mandjelia</normalizedToken>
, is identical to that figured by 
<bibRefCitation author="Samuelson, GA" editor="Jolivet, P" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="7" pageNumber="72" pagination="93 - 102" title="Acronymolpus, a new genus of Eumolpinae, endemic to New Caledonia (Coleoptera, Chrysomelidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.547.9698" volume="547" volumeTitle="Research on Chrysomelidae 5." year="2015">Samuelson (2015)</bibRefCitation>
from a specimen from Mt. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Panié">Panie</normalizedToken>
(Fig. 1f). This spermatheca is very similar to that of 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. bertiae" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" rank="species" species="bertiae">A. bertiae</taxonomicName>
, but shows some relevant differences, including a straight nodulus longer than cornu, conspicuously dilated at base and constricted medially at both ends of bulging insertion of spermathecal gland. Here, the first complete description of the penis of 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. jourdani" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" rank="species" species="jourdani">A. jourdani</taxonomicName>
is provided and is a very useful character to distinguish this species from 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. bertiae" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" rank="species" species="bertiae">A. bertiae</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 1b, d). The penis is similar to that of 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. bertiae" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" rank="species" species="bertiae">A. bertiae</taxonomicName>
with a less pronounced 
<pageBreakToken pageId="4" pageNumber="69" start="start">ventral</pageBreakToken>
curvature and more gradually curved apex; and the apical end, as seen in dorsal view, has straight sides converging to an acute apex with a deep, narrow median cleft.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="69">
As before, three taxonomic acts are required, the first transferring 
<taxonomicName authority="Baly, 1867" authorityName="Baly" authorityYear="1867" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Stethotes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Stethotes jourdani" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jourdani">Stethotes jourdani</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName authority="Samuelson, 2015" authorityName="Samuelson" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Acronymolpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acronymolpus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Acronymolpus</taxonomicName>
, to propose the new combination 
<taxonomicName authority="Samuelson, 2015" authorityName="Samuelson" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Acronymolpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acronymolpus jourdani" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jourdani">Acronymolpus jourdani</taxonomicName>
(Jolivet, Verma &amp; Mille, 2013), comb. n., and the second establishing that 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. gressitti" pageId="4" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="gressitti">A. gressitti</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. joliveti" pageId="4" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="joliveti">A. joliveti</taxonomicName>
are junior synonyms of this taxon, thus 
<taxonomicName authority="Baly, 1867" authorityName="Baly" authorityYear="1867" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Stethotes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Stethotes jourdani" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jourdani">Stethotes jourdani</taxonomicName>
Jolivet, Verma &amp; Mille, 2013 = 
<taxonomicName authority="Samuelson, 2015" authorityName="Samuelson" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Acronymolpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acronymolpus gressitti" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gressitti">Acronymolpus gressitti</taxonomicName>
Samuelson, 2015, syn. n. and 
<taxonomicName authority="Samuelson, 2015" authorityName="Samuelson" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Acronymolpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acronymolpus joliveti" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="joliveti">Acronymolpus joliveti</taxonomicName>
Samuelson, 2015, syn. n.
</paragraph>
